<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">AFFIDAVIT OF SAAD DOUAB</TI>
<P>I, Saad Douab, of the City of Ottawa, in the Province of Ontario, SOLEMNLY AFFIRM THAT:</P>
<P>1. I am an auditor with the Offshore Compliance Division in the International and Ottawa Tax Services Office of the Canada Revenue Agency (the &ldquo;CRA&rdquo;).</P>
<P>2. In the course of my work as an auditor, one of my main roles is to conduct income tax compliance audits. An income tax compliance audit is an audit of tax returns and filings filed by a taxpayer to review the appropriateness of assessments issued by the CRA, which are based on those returns and filings. The purpose of an audit process is to verify and confirm that the returns and filings comply with all relevant provisions of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM> (the &ldquo;<EM>Act</EM>&rdquo;). One of my main duties in conducting an audit is to contact the taxpayer, or their representative, and request specific documentation, books and records which support the amounts reported and claimed in the taxpayer's income tax returns and filings.</P>
<P>3. I have access to the tax files and records of the CRA pertaining to the Respondent and as such have personal knowledge of the matters to which I hereinafter depose, save and except what is stated to be on information and belief, and where so stated, I verily believe them to be true.</P>
<P>4. On September 2, 2016, I was assigned conduct of an income tax compliance audit of the Respondent, for the 2006 to 2015 taxation years.</P>
<P>5. In order to conduct the income tax compliance audit of the Respondent, I needed to review various books, records and documents to verify that the taxpayer's income tax filings and returns were in compliance with relevant provisions of the <EM>Act</EM>.</P>
<P>6. On September 16, 2016, I sent a letter via registered mail to the Respondent advising him of an income tax compliance audit of his personal income tax years for the period from January 1, 2006 to December 31, 2015. The letter contained a questionnaire seeking information, books and records which I would need to conduct the income tax compliance audit (the &ldquo;Demand Letter&rdquo;). The Demand Letter was issued pursuant to ss. 231.1 (1) of the <EM>Act</EM>. A copy of this letter, including the questionnaire, is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>7. On October 11, 2016, I received a faxed T1013 from the Respondent, authorizing his daughter Lin Lin to act as his representative with respect to the compliance audit for the Respondent's 2006 to 2015 taxation years. A copy of the faxed T1013 authorizing Lin Lin is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>8. On October 21, 2016, I received a fax from Sean Hu which enclosed a T1013 form authorizing Mr. Hu (the &ldquo;Representative&rdquo;) to represent the Respondent with respect to the income tax compliance audit. In a letter attached to the fax, the Representative advised he had written to the Minister of National Revenue (the &ldquo;Minister&rdquo;) challenging the legality of the audit and requested that the audit of the Respondent's tax returns be put on hold until a response had been received from the Minister. A copy of the Representative's documents faxed on October 21, 2016, is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>9. On October 25, 2016, the Representative called to confirm that his fax had been received. I confirmed it had been received and that we would follow up with him soon.</P>
<P>10. On November 7, 2016, I sent the Representative a letter advising that, despite his request to have the audit put on hold, the audit would proceed as planned and reiterated the demand for the Respondent to provide the information requested in the Demand Letter. A copy of my letter dated November 7, 2016, is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;D&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>11. On November 17, 2016, I received a fax from the Representative requesting a one month extension to submit the Respondent's responses and documents as requested in the Demand Letter on the basis that the Respondent had recently undergone surgery in China. A copy of the November 17, 2016, letter is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;E&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>12. On November 18, 2016, I sent the Representative a letter advising that the requested extension of time was allowed and that the Respondent was to provide the requested information and documents no later than December 17, 2016. A copy of the letter dated November 18, 2016, is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;F&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>13. On December 16, 2016, the Representative sent me a letter advising that the Respondent had concerns regarding the audit. In that fax, the Representative also asked me questions about the questionnaire contained in the Demand Letter. A copy of the December 16, 2016, letter is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;G&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>14. On January 12, 2017, I sent a letter to the Representative replying to the issues raised in his letter dated December 16, 2016. I also requested that the Respondent provide the information requested in the Demand Letter by January 20, 2017. A copy of the documents I faxed on January 12, 2017, is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>15. On January 17, 2017, I received a letter from the Representative that contained additional questions in relation to the questionnaire contained in the Demand Letter as well as a request for a 6 months extension for the Respondent to provide the information and documents requested in the Demand Letter. A copy of the Representative's letter dated January 17, 2017, is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;I&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>16. On April 5, 2017, I sent a letter to the Representative reiterating our request under s. 231.1 of the <EM>Act</EM> for the Respondent to provide the information requested in the Demand Letter and I advised that should the Respondent fail to comply within 30 days, the CRA could pursue a compliance order in Federal Court pursuant to s. 231.7 of the <EM>Act</EM>. A copy of the April 5, 2017, letter is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;J&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>17. On May 4, 2017, I received a letter from the Representative raising numerous concerns, including a suspicion that the audit conducted by the CRA was a fraud. A copy of the letter dated May 4, 2017, is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;K&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>18. On May 17, 2017, my team leader, Matthew Covey and I had a phone conversation with, the Representative to discuss the issues raised in his letter dated May 4, 2017. During that conversation the Representative requested an in-person audit interview during which he would provide to us the Respondent's answers to the questionnaire contained in the Demand Letter.</P>
<P>19. On May 18, 2017, my team leader, Matthew Covey, faxed a letter to the Representative proposing that the in-person interview occur either on June 1 or June 2, 2017, at the Toronto East Tax Services Office. A copy of the letter sent on May 18, 2017, is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;L&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>20. On May 19, 2017, the Representative responded to our interview request letter dated May 18, 2017, advising that he would attend the meeting which he requested be held on June 2, 2017. A copy of the letter sent on May 19, 2017, is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;M&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>21. Also on May 19, 2017, Mr. Covey sent a fax to the Representative confirming the date of the meeting on June 2, 2017, and advised that his expectation was that the Respondent would be in attendance. A copy of the fax sent on May 19, 2017, is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;N&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>22. On June 2, 2017, my team leader Matthew Covey and I attended the meeting in Toronto with the Representative. The Respondent did not attend the meeting nor did he provide the documents requested.</P>
<P>23. On June 7, 2017, I received a letter from the Representative dated May 4, 2017, as a follow up from the June 2, 2017, meeting. In his letter, the Representative requested another extension of time for the Respondent to provide the remainder of the information and documents sought in the Demand Letter. A copy of the letter dated May 4, 2017, is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;O&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>24. On June 20, 2017, I sent a letter to the Representative giving the Respondent until August 18, 2017, to produce the information and documents requested in the Demand Letter, and that should the Respondent fail to do so, a Compliance Order under ss. 231.7(1) of the <EM>Act</EM> would be sought in Federal Court. A copy of this letter dated June 20, 2017, is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;P&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>25. On July 4, 2017, I received a letter from the Representative in which he invoked various reasons for the Respondent not to comply with the Demand Letter. A copy of this letter dated July 4, 2017, is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;Q&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>26. On July 7, 2017, my team leader Matthew Covey and I called the Representative to get some clarification on his July 4, 2017, letter.</P>
<P>27. On August 4, 2017, I sent a letter to the Representative which addressed each of the issues raised in his July 4, 2017, letter, and reiterated CRA's demand for the information and documents requested in the Demand Letter pursuant to s. 231.1 of the <EM>Act</EM> by August 18, 2017. A copy of the August 4, 2017, letter is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;R&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>28. On August 11, 2017, I received another letter from the Representative arguing about the validity of the audit. A copy of the August 11, 2017, letter is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;S&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>29. By August 18, 2017, I had not received the information requested in the Demand Letter.</P>
<P>30. In the days that followed, I decided to initiate a request to the Department of Justice to pursue a compliance order pursuant to ss. 231.7 of the <EM>ITA</EM>.</P>
<P>31. On November 16, 2017, the Director of the of the International and Ottawa Tax Service office sent a letter to the Department of Justice, Tax Law Services, requesting that a compliance order application be pursued in this matter. C&ea;dric Renaud-Lafrance, counsel with the Department of Justice, Tax Law Services, contacted me and advised that he would assume carriage of this matter.</P>
<P>32. On December 1, 2017, C&ea;dric Renaud-Lafrance, counsel for the Applicant, sent a letter to the Respondent informing her that should she not provide the information and documentation requested in the Demand Letter by December 20, 2017, his instructions were to commence a compliance order application to enforce the Demand Letter. A copy of this letter was forwarded to me and is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;T&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>33. On December 20, 2017, the Representative responded to Mr. Renaud-Lafrance by way of letter but did not provide the information and documents as requested in the Demand Letter. A copy of this letter dated December 20, 2017, is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;U&rdquo;</BOLD> to this affidavit.</P>
<P>34. To date, I have still not received all of the books, records or information as set out in the Demand Letter sent pursuant to ss. 231.1(1) of the <EM>Act</EM>.</P>
<P>35. The Demand Letter I have sent to the Respondent pursuant to ss. 231.1(1) of the <EM>Act</EM> are for the purpose of conducting the civil income tax compliance audit. As an auditor with the Offshore Compliance, Audit Division, I only conduct civil income tax compliance audits. I do not conduct investigations concerning criminal offences under the <EM>Act</EM>.</P>
<P>36. I make this affidavit in support of the Notice of Summary Application and for no other or improper use.</P>
