<P>19. Attached see <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;</BOLD> ICES Traveler History&mdash;ATIP Traveler Passage Report from 2006/01 to 2015/12/31.</P>
<P>20. Attached see <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;D&rdquo;</BOLD> is a document in Chinese that is identical to <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P>21. Attached see <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;E&rdquo;</BOLD> is a copy of my old Chinese passport.</P>
<P>22. Attached see <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;F&rdquo;</BOLD> is a copy of my recent Chinese passport.</P>
<P>23. From 2005 to present, for the purpose of diversifying investments and funds, I acquired two townhouses for rental purposes under my wife, Min Wang's name, three jointly owned townhouses for rental purposes with my wife in Guelph, Ontario, where my wife maintained the responsibility of managing the rental properties.</P>
<P>24. Attached, see <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;G&rdquo;</BOLD> for the particulars of these properties.</P>
<P>25. I have filed tax returns in Canada.</P>
<P>26. In 2012, I quit my job at Shenzhen Kondarl (group) Co. LTD and started as a venture capitalist, investing in private pig farms with my brother in South China.</P>
<P>27. I have three real estate properties in Shenzhen, Guangdong, China.</P>
<P>28. I have significant ties to China, including a permanent residence, which has always been available to me.</P>
<P>29. My daughter, Lin Lin, lives presently in one of my properties in China as she takes care of my mother who has Alzheimer's.</P>
<P>30. My job is located in China, I have insurance, bank accounts, a driver's license, my professional network, and professional associations in China.</P>
<P>31. I live in one of the aforementioned properties and leased out the other two for rental income.</P>
<P>32. At all times, my life has been centered in Shenzhen, Guangdong, China, and not in Canada:
<P1>a. I have always been living permanently in my condo in Shenzhen that has been available to me at all times,</P1>
<P1>b. All of my extended family has been living in Henan, China, where I was bom, with the exception of my elder brother, who has been working as a business partner in Shenzhen, Guangdong, China,</P1>
<P1>c. I have dedicated a significant amount of time and energy in support of my career in the Agricultural industry in Guangdong, China, relying on my education, experiences, and social network in Shenzhen Kondarl (group) Co. LTD.</P1>
<P1>d. In 1999 to 2015, I was elected to be the vice-chairman for the Guangdong Pig Industry Association, overseeing and regulating the Pig Industry in the province of Guangdong, where I maintained a good reputation and great respect from my peers in the Pig Industry.</P1>
<P1>e. In 2000 to 2012, I was elected to be the vice-chairman for the City of Shenzhen Livestock Industry Association.</P1></P>
<P>33. I have never carried on business in Canada.</P>
<P>34. I do not have any credit cards in Canada.</P>
<P>35. I have one joint savings account with my wife, Min Wang, for convenience.</P>
<P>36. I have a driver's license in Canada for convenience purposes.</P>
<P>37. The family has two automobiles in Canada, however one is registered under my wife's name and the other is registered under my daughter's name.</P>
<P>38. I am not fluent in the English language.</P>
<P>39. I am a Chinese citizen, and not a citizen of Canada.</P>
<P>40. For reasons of convenience, I have renewed my permanent resident card twice since landing in Canada in 2005.</P>
<P>41. I have decided not to renew my current permanent resident card, as I will not be able to fulfill the residency obligation for renewal, and due to the present issuance of a 10-year visa, I will no longer need the convenience of the permanent residence card in order to visit my family in Canada.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Interactions with CRA</UNDER></TI>
<P>42. I received a letter from CRA addressed to me, dated September 16, 2016, and reviewed the letter with my authorized representative Sean Hu, CPA CGA.</P>
<P>43. Mr. Hu indicated that he had concerns regarding the enforceability of the letter because the letter did not meet the criteria of section 231.1, since the letter is addressed to me personally, and &ldquo;other entities&rdquo; and as a result, the Minister cannot satisfy paragraph 231.7(1)(a) because I am not a person who &ldquo;was required to under 231.1 or 231.2 to provide the access, assistance, information or document and did not do so&rdquo;.</P>
<P>44. Further we discussed the broad language of the questionnaire, and the inability to understand exactly what CRA is requesting in terms of information.</P>
<P>45.1had extensive discussions with Sean Hu with respect to my residency in Canada for tax purposes.</P>
<P>46. As a result, we determined that I was a resident of China for tax purposes.</P>
<P>47. To support my position that I am a resident of China for tax purposes, I provided Sean Hu with a great deal of information that enabled him to write up a three page letter that he would submit on my behalf to CRA at the June 2, 2017 meeting.</P>
<P>48. The three page document dated May 31, 2017 is entitled &ldquo;Determination of Mr. Xue Lin's Residency for Tax Purpose&rdquo;.</P>
<P>49. I have discussed with my authorized representative that I have never been a resident of Canada for tax purposes, since I have always lived and worked in China, and infrequently come to Canada to visit my wife and my daughter.</P>
<P>50. Sean Hu, my authorized representative, continued to have verbal and written discussions with CRA expressing his concerns regarding the September 16, 2016 letter, due to the general and broad language of the questionnaire.</P>
<P>51. Further Mr. Hu advised that he continued to express his concerns continually in order to better ascertain what specifically was being requested.</P>
<P>52. My authorized representative secured a few extensions of time in order to secure documents and information for CRA.</P>
<P>53. My representative advised me that it is unusual that CRA did not have an initial interview with me, and my representative requested either a transfer of my file a to Toronto Tax Service Office, or for the auditor to come from Ottawa to have a meeting in person.</P>
<P>54. My representative advised me that he secured a meeting on June 2, 2017 and that I would be presenting the auditor, Saad Douab, with banking documents and the completed questionnaire.</P>
<P>55. On June 2, 2017, my wife attended the meeting with Sean Hu, CPA CGA, Matthew Covey, the CRA Team Leader, and the auditor, Saad Douab.</P>
<P>56. At the meeting, Mr. Hu and my wife stated that no submissions would be made on my behalf, other than stating that I am a non-resident of Canada for tax purposes.</P>
<P>57. I have always worked and lived in China, and infrequently come to Canada to visit my wife and daughter for very brief periods of time.</P>
<P>58. At that point my wife and the authorized representative were under the impression that this satisfied the requirements of the CRA Team Leader and the Auditor.</P>
<P>59. At the end of the meeting they provided my wife with a letter dated June 2, 2017, which is attached <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo;</BOLD>, and as I understood it, I was required to answer new additional questions surrounding the June 2, 2017 letter.</P>
<P>60. Some time went by and my representative contacted me, stating that we had not satisfied the September 16, 2016 letter and questionnaire.</P>
<P>61. My representative and I were confused because we thought that we had already satisfied those requirements at the meeting on June 2, 2017.</P>
<P>62. As a result, my representative communicated to CRA that there was some confusion surrounding the September 16, 2016 letter and June 2, 2017 letter and he further asked CRA what information was still outstanding and he advised that CRA did not answer our questions in terms of what documents or information were still outstanding, however I still wanted to comply.</P>
<P>63. My representative further advised me that the Department of Justice had sent a letter indicating that the September 16, 2016 questionnaire was not satisfactorily answered and that they wanted an answer by a certain deadline and my representative advised me that he wrote a letter asking what specifically was needed to comply and he received no response.</P>
<P>64. I understand that my authorized representative attempted to secure CRA's and the Department of Justice's determination of my residency for tax purposes prior to dealing with the request of information pursuant to CRA's letter dated September 16, 2016 and the questionnaire.</P>
<P>65. At all times I wanted to comply with my obligations pursuant to the ITA.</P>
<P>66. I make this affidavit in response to the applicant's motion herein and make this affidavit for no improper purpose.</P>
