<BLOCK1><TI>AFFIDAVIT OF SEAN HU</TI>
<P><BOLD>I, Sean Hu,</BOLD> of the City of Toronto, in the Province of Ontario, in Canada, <BOLD>HEREBY MAKE OATH AND SAY:</BOLD>
<P1>1. I am a Public Chartered Accountant for Lin Lin, Xue Lin and Min Wang.</P1>
<P1>2. Where I express opinions in this Affidavit, those are founded on my experience, my discussions with Ming Wang, Xue Lin, Lin Lin and CRA representatives.</P1>
<P1>3. Where I make statements in the context of this Affidavit that are not within my personal knowledge, I identify the source of the information and verily believe the information to be true.</P1>
<P1>4. Min Wang, Lin Lin and Xue Lin reached out to me to retain my advice regarding a tax matter.</P1>
<P1>5. I reviewed the letter of September 16, 2016 and the questionnaire.</P1>
<P1>6. I indicated that I had concerns regarding the enforceability of the letter because the letter did not meet the criteria of section 231.1 since the letter is addressed to my clients personally, as well as &ldquo;other entities&rdquo; were referred to, and as a result, the Minister cannot satisfy paragraph 231.7(1)(a) because the person who &ldquo;was required to under 231.1 or 231.2 to provide the access, assistance, information or document and did not do so&rdquo; is not ascertainable.</P1>
<P1>7. Further we discussed the broad language of the questionnaire, and the inability to understand exactly what CRA is requesting in terms of information, I advised the clients to secure as many documents with respect to the September 16, 2016 letter and the questionnaire, so I did so.</P1>
<P1>8. We discussed the fact that Xue Lin has never been a resident of Canada for tax purposes, since he has always lived and worked in China.</P1>
<P1>9. I was instructed by Min Wang, Lin Lin and Xue Lin to contact CRA both orally and in written format in order to provide them with comprehensive advice in order to act on their behalf.</P1>
<P1>10. I had a series of communications with CRA in which I advised them of the aforementioned concerns.</P1>
<P1>11. After receiving the auditor's letter dated April 5, 2017, I spoke with my clients and agreed to submit the information and documents as requested, however I still had many concerns regarding the security of the documents if sent by mail, so I sent a letter on May 4, 2017, to the auditor, expressing such concerns.</P1>
<P1>12. I advised my clients that it is unusual that CRA did not start the interaction with the taxpayers first and I advised the auditor that we requested a meeting in person.</P1>
<P1>13. I requested that the auditor located in Ottawa to (1) either transfer the file to Toronto in order to meet in Toronto, or (2) that the auditor located in Ottawa could come to Toronto to meet.</P1>
<P1>14. A week leader, the team leader, Matthew Covey, called me and told me that he and the auditor, Saad Douab, would come to Toronto to meet, and we would submit our documents then.</P1>
<P1>15. Upon confirming the date of said meeting, I was advised that Min Wang would appear on behalf of her husband and daughter.</P1>
<P1>16. CRA did not make it mandatory for my clients to attend, but Min Wang attended in person with the necessary banking documents, completed questionnaire, and answered questions on behalf of herself and her daughter.</P1>
<P1>17. I had extensive discussions with Xue Lin with respect to his residency in Canada for tax purposes.</P1>
<P1>18. As a result, Xue Lin provided me with a great deal of information that enabled me to make a three page written submission on his behalf to CRA on June 2, 2017, entitled &ldquo;Determination of Mr. Xue Lin's Residency for Tax Purpose&rdquo; dated May 31, 2017.</P1>
<P1>19. Min Wang came for the meeting and at the beginning of the meeting she submitted the documents and completed questionnaires to the CRA officials.</P1>
<P1>20. The CRA officials went through every question on the questionnaire and looked at the documents.</P1>
<P1>21. During the meeting, the auditor gave Min Wang three sets of letters dated June 2, 2017.</P1>
<P1>22. I have advised CRA both verbally and in writing that my husband, Xue Lin, is not a resident for tax purposes.</P1>
<P1>23. I explained to the CRA officials that Xue Lin, has always worked and lived in China, and infrequently comes to Canada to visit his family.</P1>
<P1>24. In the June 2, 2017 letter, the taxpayers were asked to explain some amounts of incoming funds deposited or credited to their bank accounts.</P1>
<P1>25. From that point on my understanding was that we had met the requirements of the September 16, 2016 letter, and now had to focus on the June 2, 2017 letter's questions, but that we needed some more time, as expressed in my June 7, 2017 letter.</P1>
<P1>26. However, I received a letter dated June 20, 2017 from the auditor with no reference to the June 2, 2017 letter's requirements.</P1>
<P1>27. In my letter dated July 4, 2017, I followed up with CRA regarding their determination of Xue Lin's residency in Canada for tax purpose.</P1>
<P1>28. The auditor's August 4, 2017 letter showed that they had intended to start over with their old package of demands outlined in the initial letter and that they had abandoned the June 2, 2017 requirements.</P1>
<P1>29. At that time, my understanding was that the information and documents that Min Wang provided to Mr. Covey on June 2, 2017 had substantially met the requirements of the initial letter.</P1>
<P1>30. Several things were clear to me: (1) the questionnaires were completed; (2) bank statements of various banks were provided; and (3) no documents from Xue Lin were provided because he is a non-resident for the purpose of taxation in Canada.</P1>
<P1>31. In order to let the taxpayers know how to comply with what the auditor wanted, I asked the auditor to let me know what documents were outstanding in my letter to the Auditor, dated August 11, 2018.</P1>
<P1>32. I was expecting the auditor to give me a clear answer, however he did not get back to me.</P1>
<P1>33. Then I received a letter dated December 1, 2017 from the Justice Department lawyer making the same demand without the intention to answer my question.</P1>
<P1>34. In my letter dated December 20, 2017, I once again asked the lawyer to clarify which documents were being demanded, yet I received no response as to what particular documents or information were outstanding.</P1>
<P1>35. In particular, I stated in the aforementioned letter that firstly CRA has to establish Xue Lin's residency in Canada for the purpose of taxation before discussion could begin regarding requests for information pursuant to the September 16, 2016 letter and the attached questionnaire.</P1>
<P1>36. As the request was unclear, there was no way to comply.</P1>
<P1>37. I make this affidavit in response to the applicant's motion herein and make this affidavit for no improper purpose.</P1></P>
