<BLOCK1><TI>AFFIDAVIT OF MIN WANG</TI>
<P><BOLD>I, Min Wang</BOLD>, of the City of Puslinch, in the Province of Ontario, in Canada, <BOLD>HEREBY MAKE OATH AND SAY:</BOLD></P>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Background</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. Where I make statements in the context of this Affidavit that are not within my personal knowledge, I identify the source of the information and verily believe the information to be true.</P>
<P>2. I reside at XXXXXXXXXX.</P>
<P>3. I was born in XXXXXXXXXX in Nanzhao, in the province of Henan, in the People's Republic of China (&ldquo;China&rdquo;).</P>
<P>4. I am the wife of Xue Lin and the mother of Lin Lin.</P>
<P>5. I received my undergraduate education in Henan University of Animal Husbandry and Economy.</P>
<P>6. After graduation, in 1983, I became a lecture instructor at Henan University of Animal Husbandry and Economy.</P>
<P>7. In 1986, I married Xue Lin and gave birth to my only daughter, Lin Lin, in December 1987.</P>
<P>8. I pursued post-graduate studies in South China Agricultural University from 1993 to 1995, and obtained a master's degree in science majoring in animal nutrition.</P>
<P>9. I started working in the field of animal feed from 1995 all the way to July 2005 in Shenzhen, Guangdong, China.</P>
<P>10. In May of 2004, I made an application for permanent residence in China on behalf of myself, my husband and my daughter.</P>
<P>11. The purpose behind coming to Canada was so that our daughter could get a better education in Canada.</P>
<P>12. I came with my family to Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada in July 2005.</P>
<P>13. In Canada, my daughter attended high school for grades 11 and 12, and completed her undergrad and postgrad education.</P>
<P>14. In order to support the family, my husband, Xue Lin, flew back to China two weeks after landing in Canada, in July 2005, to continue his career.</P>
<P>15. My husband, Xue Lin, has always worked and resided in China.</P>
<P>16. Since 2005, I have been working at Chinese restaurants, volunteering at the University of Guelph as a lab assistant, and attending ESL school in my spare time.</P>
<P>17. I have substantial ties to Canada, including my principle residence, a few rental properties that I manage, personal belongings, a vehicle, insurance, bank accounts and a driver's license in Canada.</P>
<P>18. Beginning in 2005, using funds from my husband, from China, several investment houses for rental purpose were bought under my name, my daughter's name and jointly with my husband.</P>
<P>19. These aforementioned rental properties are all in Ontario and I took care of all the rental properties.</P>
<P>20. Attached is <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;A</BOLD>&rdquo;, which lists all of the properties that were purchased in my name.</P>
<P>21. Xue Lin and I bought a house in Guelph in September 2005 and decided I would stay with my daughter while she went to high school in Guelph, Ontario.</P>
<P>22. My husband, Xue Lin, paid a short visit to Canada in September 2005 for the closing of the house.</P>
<P>23. This house became a rental property in 2007 when my daughter, Lin Lin, moved into a new house and was sold in 2018.</P>
<P>24. Since 2007, using fonds from my husband, Xue, two rental townhouses were bought solely under my name and three rental townhouses were bought under both my name and my husband, Xue's, and two of them were sold in 2018.</P>
<P>25. In 2010, a house in Guelph, Ontario was purchased under my name, using fonds from my husband from China, which was used as a principal residence for myself and our daughter, Lin, and was later sold in 2015.</P>
<P>26. I moved into a new house that I jointly owned with my husband, using fonds from the sale of the old home.</P>
<P>27. In 2018, I obtained paid employment at the University of Guelph as a lab assistant.</P>
<P>28. For the duration of these years, my major sources of income have been employment income, rental income and investment income from mutual fonds at TD Canada Trust.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Interactions with CRA</UNDER></TI>
<P>29. I received a letter from CRA dated September 16, 2016, and reviewed the letter with my representative Sean Hu, CPA CGA.</P>
<P>30. Mr. Hu indicated that he had concerns regarding the enforceability of the letter because the letter did not meet the criteria of section 231.1 since the letter is addressed to me personally, and &ldquo;other entities&rdquo; and as a result, the Minister cannot satisfy paragraph 231.7(1) because I am not a person who &ldquo;was required to under 231.1 or 231.2 to provide the access, assistance, information or document and did not do so&rdquo;.</P>
<P>31. Further we discussed the broad language of the questionnaire, and the inability to understand exactly what CRA is requesting in terms of information, however Mr. Hu advised me to secure as many documents with respect to the September 16, 2016 letter and the questionnaire, so I did so.</P>
<P>32. We discussed that my husband has never been a resident of Canada for tax purposes, since he has always lived and worked in China.</P>
<P>33. Sean Hu continued to have verbal and written discussions with CRA expressing his concerns regarding the September 16, 2016 letter.</P>
<P>34. Further Mr. Hu advised that he continued to express his concerns continually in order to better ascertain what specifically was being requested.</P>
<P>35. My authorized representative secured a few extensions of time in order for me to secure documents and information for CRA.</P>
<P>36. My representative advised me that it is unusual that CRA did not have an initial interview with me, and my representative requested either a transfer of my file a to Toronto Tax Service Office, or for the auditor to come from Ottawa to have a meeting in person.</P>
<P>37. My representative advised me that he secured a meeting on June 2, 2017 and that I would be presenting the auditor, Saad Douab, with banking documents and the completed questionnaire.</P>
<P>38. On June 2, 2017, I attended the meeting with Sean Hu, CPA CGA, Matthew Covey, the CRA Team Leader, and the auditor, Saad Douab.</P>
<P>39. I provided my completed questionnaire and bank documents.</P>
<P>40. Additionally, I provided the completed questionnaire and bank documents for my daughter, Lin Lin.</P>
<P>41. At the meeting, Mr. Hu and I stated that only the documents relating to myself and my daughter, Lin Lin, would be submitted, and that no submissions would be made on behalf of my husband, Xue Lin, is a non-resident of Canada for tax purposes.</P>
<P>42. My husband has always worked and lived in China, and infrequently comes to Canada to visit my daughter for a very brief period of time.</P>
<P>43. We reviewed the answers to the questionnaires and they asked a series of questions with respect to the documents and I provided answers on behalf of my daughter and myself.</P>
<P>44. At that point I was under the impression that this satisfied the requirements of the CRA Team Leader and the Auditor.</P>
<P>45. I was not provided with a receipt confirming that said documentation had been provided, nor that the submitted answers to the questionnaires had also been provided.</P>
<P>46. At the end of the meeting they provided me with a letter dated June 2, 2017, which is attached <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;B</BOLD>&rdquo;, and as I understood it, I was required to answer new additional questions surrounding the June 2, 2017 letter.</P>
<P>47. Some time went by and my representative contacted me, stating that we had not satisfied the September 16, 2016 letter and questionnaire.</P>
<P>48. My representative and I were confused because we thought that we had already satisfied those requirements at the meeting on June 2, 2017.</P>
<P>49. As a result, my representative communicated to CRA that there was some confusion surrounding the September 16, 2016 letter and June 2, 2017 letter and he further asked CRA what information was still outstanding and he advised me that CRA did not answer his question in terms of what documents or information was still outstanding, however I still wanted to comply.</P>
<P>50. My representative further advised me the Department of Justice sent a letter indicating that the September 16, 2016 questionnaire was not satisfactorily answered and that they wanted an answer by a certain deadline and my representative advised me that he wrote a letter asking what specifically was needed to comply and he received no response.</P>
<P>51. At all times I wanted to comply with my obligations pursuant to the ITA.</P>
<P>52. I make this affidavit in response to the applicant's motion herein and make this affidavit for no improper purpose.</P>
