<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I"><UNDER>OVERVIEW</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. Parliament has granted the Minister of National Revenue broad powers to require any person to provide information and documentation for the purpose of the Minister conducting an audit to determine if a taxpayer's income tax filings and the assessments issued by the Minister are in compliance with the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>. These powers are necessary for the administration and enforcement of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM> and to otherwise preserve the integrity of the self-reporting system.</P>
<P>2. In the present case, the Respondent has failed to produce all of the books, records and information which the Canada Revenue Agency requested he produce in the course of an income tax compliance audit of her 2006 to 2015 taxation years. The request for books and records was made under the authority granted pursuant to s. 231.1(1) of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>.</P>
<P>3. An initial request letter dated September 16, 2016 was duly issued by the Minister requesting production of the Respondent's information for the period under audit. Despite numerous follow up letters reminding the Respondent of his obligation to provide the information requested, the Respondent has failed to fully comply with the request letter.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II"><UNDER>PART 1&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</UNDER></TI>
<P>4. In September 2016, the Canada Revenue Agency (the &ldquo;CRA&rdquo;) commenced an audit of the personal income tax returns of the Respondent for the 2006 to 2015 taxation years.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Saad Douab, affirmed September 10, 2018 (&ldquo;Douab Affidavit&rdquo;), Application Record, Tab 2, para. 4.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>5. On September 16, 2016, Saad Douab, auditor at the CRA (the &ldquo;Auditor&rdquo;), via Priority Post, sent a demand letter to the Respondent advising her of an audit of her personal income taxation years 2006 to 2015 (the &ldquo;Demand Letter&rdquo;). The Demand Letter was issued pursuant to ss. 231.1(1) of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RSC 1985, c 1 (5<SUP>th</SUP> Supp).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> (the &ldquo;<EM>Act</EM>&rdquo;) and contained a questionnaire seeking information, books and records needed to conduct the audit. The Auditor requested that the information requested in the Demand Letter be provided by October 21, 2016.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 6 and Exhibit A.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>6. On October 11, 2016, the Auditor received a faxed T1013 from the Respondent, authorizing his daughter Lin Lin to act as his representative with respect to the compliance audit for the Respondent's 2006 to 2015 taxation years.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 7 and Exhibit B.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>7. On October 21, 2016, the Auditor received a fax from a certain Sean Hu which enclosed a letter and a T1013 form authorizing Mr. Hu (the &ldquo;Representative&rdquo;) to act as the Respondent's representative with respect to her income tax compliance audit. As part of that fax, the Representative informed the Auditor that he had written to the Minister of National Revenue (the &ldquo;Minister&rdquo;) challenging the legality of the audit and requested that the audit of the Respondent's tax returns be put on hold until a response had been received from the Minister.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 8 and Exhibit C.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>8. On October 25, 2016, the Representative called the Auditor to confirm receipt of his fax. The Auditor confirmed receipt of the fax and advised the Representative that a response would be forthcoming.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 9.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>9. On November 7, 2016, the Auditor wrote to the Representative advising that the audit would proceed as planned. The Auditor also granted the Respondent a 10 day extension of time to November 17, 2016, to provide the information requested in the Demand Letter.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 10, and Exhibit D</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>10. On November 17, 2016, the Representative faxed a letter to the Auditor requesting a one month extension of time. The reason provided for the need of an extension was that the Respondent had undergone surgery in China.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 11, and Exhibit E.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>11. On November 18, 2016, the Auditor granted the requested extension of time and set December 17, 2016 as the new deadline for the Respondent to comply with the Demand Letter.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 12 and Exhibit F.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>12. On December 16, 2016, the Representative faxed a letter to the Auditor advising that the Respondent had concerns regarding the audit and requested clarification concerning some of the questions asked in the questionnaire that was attached to the Demand Letter.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 13 and Exhibit G.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>13. On January 12, 2017, the Auditor wrote back to the Representative, responding to the Representative's latest letter. The Auditor set a new deadline of January 20, 2017 for the Respondent to provide the information originally requested in the Demand Letter by January 20, 2017.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 14 and Exhibit H.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>14. On January 17, 2017, the Auditor received a letter from the Representative which contained additional questions with respect to the questionnaire attached to the Demand Letter as well as a request for a 6 months extension for the Respondent to provide the requested information and documents, arguing that additional time was required given the nature and complexity of the records being sought.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 15 and Exhibit I.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>15. On April 5, 2017, the Auditor sent a letter to the Representative responding to the questions asked in his letter dated January 17, 2017. The Auditor set the date of May 4, 2017 as the new date by which the Respondent had to comply with the Demand Letter. The Auditor advised that failure to comply within 30 days could result in the CRA pursuing a compliance order in Federal Court pursuant to s. 231.7 of the <EM>Act</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 16 and Exhibit J.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. On May 4, 2017, the Representative sent a letter to the Auditor stating that Respondent had numerous concerns regarding the legitimacy of the audit and stated that the Respondent was suspicious that the audit was fraudulent.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 17 and Exhibit K.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>17. On May 17, 2017, the Auditor, his team leader, Mr. Matthew Covey and the Representative discussed the issues raised in the Representative's letter of May 4, 2017. During this conversation, the Representative requested an in-person meeting advising that, at that time, the Respondent would provide the completed questionnaire.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 18.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>18. On May 18, 2017, Mr. Covey, faxed a letter to the Representative proposing that the in-person interview occur either on June 1 or June 2, 2017, at the Toronto East Tax Services Office. In that letter, the CRA advised the Representative of the expectation that both the Representative and his client would attend the meeting.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 19 and Exhibit L.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>19. On May 19, 2017, the Representative faxed a letter dated May 18, 2017 to Mr. Covey advising that he would attend the meeting which he requested be held on June 2, 2017.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 20 and Exhibit M.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>20. Also on May 19, 2017, Mr. Covey sent a fax to the Representative confirming the date of the meeting as June 2, 2017, and reiterated that the CRA expectation was that the Respondent would be in attendance.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 21 and Exhibit N.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>21. On June 2, 2017, the Auditor and Mr. Covey attended the meeting with the Representative. The Respondent did not attend the meeting nor did he provide the requested documents.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 22.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>22. On June 7, 2017, the Representative sent the Auditor a letter dated May 4, 2017, requesting a further 2 month extension of time arguing that the Respondent required additional time to provide the documents and information sought.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 23 and Exhibit O.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>23. On June 20, 2017, the auditor wrote to the Representative, advising that the Respondent had been granted an extension of time until August 18, 2017.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 24 and Exhibit P.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>24. On July 4, 2017, the Representative sent the Auditor a letter stating that the auditors were acting outside of the law and requested that a new letter to comply be issued by the CRA. In that letter, the Representative cited various explanations for the Respondent's noncompliance.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 25 and Exhibit Q.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>25. On July 7, 2017, the Auditor and Mr. Covey had a call with the Representative to address the purpose of his letter dated July 4, 2017.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 26.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>26. On August 4, 2017, the Auditor wrote to the Representative providing answers to each of the issues raised in his letter dated July 4, 2017. The Auditor also advised that the Demand Letter was enforceable and reiterated that the deadline for the Respondent to comply with it was August 18, 2017.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 27 and Exhibit R.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>27. On August 11, 2017, the Representative sent another letter to the Auditor questioning the validity of the audit, requesting further clarification with respect to what information was being sought and advising that the Respondent's non-compliance was a result of the CRA's lack of specificity as to what documents were being requested, in addition to the discriminatory process employed by the CRA.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 28 and Exhibit S.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>28. On December 1, 2017, C&ea;dric Renaud-Lafrance, counsel for the Applicant, sent a letter to the Representative stating that should the Respondent not provide the information and documentation requested in the Demand Letter by December 20, 2017, counsel for the Applicant had instructions to commence a compliance order application to enforce the Demand Letter.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 32 and Exhibit T.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>29. On December 20, 2017, the Representative responded to Mr. Renaud-Lafrance by way of letter but did not provide the information and documents as requested in the Demand Letter.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 33 and Exhibit U.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>30. To this date, the CRA has not received all of the books, records and information as set out in the Demand Letter.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 34.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>31. The Demand Letter the Minister has issued to the Respondent is for the purpose of conducting an audit to determine the Respondent's liability for tax for the 2006 to 2015 taxation years.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para. 35.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III"><UNDER>PART II&mdash;ISSUES</UNDER></TI>
<P>32. The issue is whether the conditions for the issuance of a compliance order under ss. 231.7(1) of the <EM>Act</EM> are met in the present case.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV"><UNDER>PART III SUBMISSIONS</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK2><TI>Minister's powers to compel production of information and documents</TI>
<P>33. Section 220 of the <EM>Act</EM> provides that the Minister has a duty to administer and enforce the <EM>Act</EM>, and in doing so assess the amount of tax payable by every person liable for tax under the <EM>Act</EM>.</P>
<P>34. The Minister's responsibility of assessing tax is not a procedural matter; it is the very essence of the <EM>Act</EM>. Any agreement by the Minister not to tax what the <EM>Act</EM> requires to be taxed would be a dereliction of his duty to enforce the <EM>Act</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Wenger's Ltd. v MNR</SOC><CITE>92 DTC 2132</CITE><COURTJUR>TCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, Application Record, Tab 5, at para. 93.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>35. The Minister must exercise these powers in a fair and even handed manner and be capable of exercising these powers whether or not he has reasonable grounds for believing that a particular taxpayer has breached the <EM>Act</EM>. Often it will be impossible to determine from the face of the return at the initial time of filing whether any impropriety has occurred in its preparation. A spot check or a system of random monitoring may be the only way in which the integrity of the tax system can be maintained. The integrity of our self-assessing tax system depends on the Minister's broad power to verify compliance with the taxing statutes.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>R v McKinlay Transport Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[1990] 1 SCR 627</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>McKinlay</EM>&rdquo;), Application Record, Tab 6, at paras. 35-36; <CASEREF><SOC>MNR v Redeemer Foundation</SOC><CITE>2006 FCA 325</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2006 DTC 6712</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF>, Application Record, Tab 7, at paras. 25&ndash;37; aff'd by <CASEREF><CITE>2008 SCC 46</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2008 DTC 6474</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF>, Application Record, Tab 7.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>36. Under ss. 231.1(1) of the <EM>Act</EM>, the Minister may, for any purpose related to the administration or enforcement of the <EM>Act</EM>, inspect, audit or examine the books and records of a taxpayer and any document of the taxpayer or of any other person that relates or may relate to the information that is or should be in the books or records of the taxpayer or to any amount payable by the taxpayer under the <EM>Act</EM>.</P>
<P>37. A person served with a request for information or requirement under these provisions is required to provide the Minister with the information or documents requested if the Minister is acting for any purpose related to the administration or enforcement of the <EM>Act</EM> and the person is given a reasonable amount of time for production of the information or documents.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Minister of National Revenue v Marshall</SOC><CITE>2006 FC 279</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Marshall</EM>&rdquo;), Application Record, Tab 8, at paras. 16.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>38. Section 231.1 of the <EM>Act</EM>, similarly to section 231.2 of the <EM>Act</EM>, provides the least intrusive means by which effective monitoring of compliance with the <EM>Act</EM> can be effected. It involves no invasion of a taxpayer's home or business premises. It simply calls for the production of records which may be relevant to the filing of an income tax return. A taxpayer's expectation of privacy with regard to these documents <EM>vis-&ag;-vis</EM> the Minister is relatively low. The Minister has no way of knowing whether certain records are relevant until he has had an opportunity to examine them.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>McKinlay</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> note 29, at para. 37.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>39. Under ss. 231.7(1) of the <EM>Act</EM>, a judge may order a person to provide any access, information, assistance or documents sought by the Minister if the judge is satisfied that the person was required to do so under ss. 231.1 of the <EM>Act</EM> to provide the access, assistance, information or document and did not do so, and the information or document is not protected from disclosure by solicitor-client privilege as defined in 232(1) of the <EM>Act</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, RSC, 1985, c 1 (5<SUP>th</SUP> Supp), see 231.7(1), Tab 3 (Appendix A) <EM>Marshall</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, note 31, at paras. 17-18.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>How these principles apply to the facts of this instance</TI>
<P>40. On September 16, 2016, the Minister sent the Demand Letter containing a questionnaire to the Respondent requesting the production of specified information, documents and records for income tax compliance audit purposes.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Douab Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, at para. 6, (Exhibit A).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Demand Letter was issued pursuant to ss. 231.1(1) of the <EM>Act</EM> for the purpose of conducting a civil income tax compliance audit to ascertain the amounts payable by the Respondent under the <EM>Act</EM>.</P>
<P>41. The Demand Letter specified October 21, 2016 as the date by which the Respondent was to produce the information, documents and records sought, a deadline the Respondent has not complied with.</P>
<P>42. The Minister granted to the Respondent numerous extension of time to submit the information, documents and records requested in the Demand Letter.</P>
<P>43. Despite being granted additional time, the Respondent continuously failed to comply with the Demand Letter and has as yet to produce all of the information, documents and records requested by the Demand Letter.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Timing of the Income Tax Compliance Audit</TI>
<P>44. There is no time limitation constraining the Minister from requesting production of records for periods exceeding the document retention periods set out in ss. 230(4) of the <EM>Act</EM> or for taxation years beyond the normal reassessment period. As confirmed by the Federal Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Tower v. Minister of National Revenue</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Tower v Minister of National Revenue</SOC><CITE>2003 FCA 307</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2003 DTC 5540</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>FCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, Application Record, Tab 9, at para. 32.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and <CASEREF><SOC>1144020 Ontario Ltd. v Minister of National Revenue</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>1144020 Ontario Ltd. v Minister of National Revenue</SOC><CITE>2005 FC 813</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2005 DTC 5315</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>FC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, Application Record, Tab 10, at para. 60.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> ss. 231.1 (1) of the <EM>Act</EM>, is not limited by any statutory time limit. If such records are still available and if the Minister seeks production of them pursuant to ss. 231.1 (1), then the records must be produced</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>No Solicitor-CIient Privilege</TI>
<P>45. Subsection 231.7(1) of the <EM>Act</EM> requires that the information, documents and records sought by the Minister are not protected from disclosure by solicitor-client privilege within the meaning of 232(1) of the <EM>Act</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>ITA</EM>, ss. 232(1), Tab 3 (Appendix A).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>These provisions clearly indicate that the privilege attaches only to communications passing between a solicitor and a client in professional confidence.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Marshall</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> note 31, Applicant's Record, Tab 8, at para. 23.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>46. Solicitor-client privilege is not an issue in this matter because the information, documents and records requested in the Demand Letter, are mostly financial and banking records, not documents that would constitute communications passing between a solicitor and a client in professional confidence.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Conclusion</TI>
<P>47. The Respondent has been given a reasonable amount of time to provide the information requested in the Demand Letter and has failed to produce all of the information, documents and records requested.</P>
<P>48. The conditions set out in subsection 231.7(1) of the <EM>Act</EM> have been satisfied. Accordingly, the Minister is entitled to an Order pursuant to 231.7(1) of the <EM>Act</EM> compelling the Respondent to produce the information and documents specified in the Demand Letter, including the questionnaire attached to it, within 15 days of the date hereof.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V"><UNDER>PART IV&mdash;ORDER SOUGHT</UNDER></TI>
<P>49. The Applicant requests an Order compelling the Respondent to provide the Applicant with the information, documents and records as set out in the draft Order at Tab 4 of the Application Record.</P>
<P>50. The Applicant requests costs of this application.</P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</P>
