<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I"><UNDER>OVERVIEW</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. The Canadian system tax is based on self-assessment and thus the Minister of National Revenue (the &ldquo;Minister&rdquo;) is required to audit the taxpayers to verify whether the taxpayers have complied with their duties and obligations under the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, RSC, 1985, c 1 [&ldquo;<EM>ITA</EM>&rdquo;].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> (hereinafter, the &ldquo;ITA&rdquo;).</P>
<P>2. The Minister has the authority to use the inspection and requirement powers under ss 231.1(1) and 231.2(1) of the ITA.</P>
<P>3. Statutory interpretation has provided for a broad interpretation of the subsection of 231.1 of the ITA.</P>
<P>4. The Minister states that subsection of 231.1 of the ITA provides for broad audit powers, but the respondent's position is that the Minister's audit powers are not unlimited.</P>
<P>5. The Minister does not have the authority in this instance to tax a resident of China based on his worldwide income, despite the fact that the Chinese national has filed Canadian tax returns in the past.</P>
<P>6. A summary application by the Minister for a compliance order under section 231.7 of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM> in relation to the respondent providing answers to the questionnaire attached to Canada Revenue Agency's letter dated September 16, 2016.</P>
<P>7. Potentially serious consequences can flow from the failure to obey a compliance order, including fines and/or imprisonment.</P>
<P>8. A compliance order can only be issued if the Minister proves that the respondent did not comply with section 231.1 of the ITA.</P>
<P>9. The respondent's position is that the Minister did not comply with section 231.1 of the ITA because the Minister did not inspect, audit and examine the books, records and property of respondent but rather requested to obtain information. Thus, the Minister should have used section 231.2 of the ITA to require or demand the information from the respondent.</P>
<P>10. In the alternative, if the Court finds that the Minister has complied with section 231.1 of the ITA, the respondent has provided partial answers to the Minister's letter and questionnaire because it is unclear what remains outstanding with respect to the September 16, 2016 letter and questionnaire, despite the authorized representative.</P>
<P>11. The respondent raises the issue of whether the conditions for the issuance of a compliance order under subsection 231.7 of the ITA are met in the present case.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II"><UNDER>PART I&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</UNDER></TI>
<P>12. On September 2, 2016, the auditor stated that he was assigned a compliance audit for the years 2006 to 2015.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Saad Douab, affirmed September 10, 2018 at para 4 [&ldquo;<EM>Douab Affidavit</EM>&rdquo;].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>13. Further, the auditor stated that in order to conduct the audit, he needed to review various books, records, and documents.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>14. The auditor stated that on September 16, 2016 he sent a registered letter to the taxpayer advising Mr. Lin of the compliance audit and that the letter included a questionnaire.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 6.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>15. Further, the auditor stated that that the compliance audit was in regards to her personal income tax returns from the period from January 1, 2006 to December 31, 2015.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit A and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 6.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. The registered letter says &ldquo;[y]our personal income tax return and any other related or associated entities&rdquo;, none of which have been named.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit A and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 6.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>17. Further, the letter states &ldquo;...[t]he Canada Revenue Agency (CRA) is in possession of information that has led us to determine that you may have offshore holdings that you have failed to disclosed as required by the Income Tax. Act.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>18. The auditor referred to the September 16, 2016 registered letter as the &ldquo;Demand Letter&rdquo; and stated that issued pursuant to subsection 231.1 of the ITA.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>19. The registered letter asks for information and makes no statement that a response is &ldquo;required&rdquo; and it does not set out the consequences for non-compliance.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>20. Once the respondent received the registered letter dated September 16, 2016, he contacted Sean Hu, C.P.A., C.G.A, with respect to securing representation.</P>
<P>21. The auditor stated that the representative advised the auditor that he sent a letter to the Minster of National Revenue with respect to challenging the legality of the audit and requested that CRA hold the matter down until he secures a response from the Minister.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit C and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 8.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>22. The auditor states that on October 25, 2016 the representative contacted him to confirm that he received his fax, and the auditor confirmed that the fax was received and &ldquo;...that we would follow up with him soon.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit D and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 10.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>23. The auditor states that in his correspondence to the taxpayer's representative dated November 7, 2016, that &ldquo;...the audit would proceed as originally planned&rdquo; and reiterated the demand for the Respondent to provide the information requested in the initial letter dated September 16, 2016.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit D and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 10.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Further, the auditor asked for &ldquo;information requested as outlined in our initial letter&rdquo; and not &ldquo;books and records&rdquo;.</P>
<P>24. In the November 7, 2016 letter, the auditor stated: &ldquo;We ask that you please provide information requested as outlined in our initial dated September 16, 2016 within 10 days of this letter.&rdquo; Again, at the time this was not stated as a &ldquo;Demand&rdquo;, but a request and no consequence presented if there is not compliance.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit D and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 10.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>25. On November 17, 2016, the representative for the respondent faxed a letter to the auditor requesting an extension of time to submit documents because the respondent had surgery in China and that he had surgery in China because he ordinarily lives in China.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit E and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 11.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>26. The auditor does not call its November 18, 2016 letter a &ldquo;Demand Letter&rdquo; and refers to &ldquo;the requested information and documents&rdquo; and provides a formal extension no later than December 17, 2016.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit F and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 12.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>27. The reply letter the dated November 18, 2016 from the auditor again refers to the &ldquo;information requested&rdquo;, not demanded or required.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit F and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 12.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>28. Further, the auditor then indicated that if the information was not received, CRA would pursue issuing a Compliance Order under subsection 231.7 of the ITA and the said letter does not state the consequences of non-compliance.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit F and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>29. In a letter dated December 16, 2016, the representative for the respondent advised auditor that he had concerns regarding the audit and thus raised questions regarding the procedural issues concerning the answering of the questions.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit F and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 12.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>30. Further, the representative for the respondent raised the issue of &ldquo;reasonable time&rdquo; if the request is made under subsection 231.6 of the Income Tax Act, which allows for a minimum of 90 days to respond.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>31. Further to the above, the representative for the respondent raised the issue about travel to meet with the auditor and a request was made to move the audit to Toronto.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>32. It took the auditor in or around four (4) weeks to reply to the representative's letter dated December 16, 2016.</P>
<P>33. On the cover page, the auditor stated that the deadline was extended once again, this time to January 20, 2017.</P>
<P>34. Further, the auditor stated that this was allowing the taxpayer more than 90 days.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit H and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 14.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>35. Further to the above, the auditor called the information &ldquo;... requested information&rdquo; and the original letter, September 16, 2016, a &ldquo;request letter&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit H and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 14.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>36. In CRA's letter dated January 12, 2017, it refers to the &ldquo;...completed information requested&rdquo; and makes no mention of the consequences of not complying with 231.7 of the Income Tax Act.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>37. Further, CRA advised the representative that &ldquo;[w]hen necessary, we will travel to your area to meet with you in due time.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>38. The auditor also references to the original letter was being dated September 22, 2016, which was not attached as an Exhibit.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>39. In the auditor's letter dated January 12, 2017 the auditor stated that CRA would be pursuing a Compliance Order despite the cover of the fax giving the respondent until January 20, 2017 to provide information requested.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>40. In a letter dated January 17, 2017, the representative for the respondent asked further questions with respect to the procedural issues surrounding the questionnaire.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>41. Further, the representative the addressed the following issues:
<P1>a. Have the personal tax returns and any other related or associated entities have been selected for audit?<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>b. Do you have the names for those entities that you are planning to audit?<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>c. The issues surrounding non-residents of Canada;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>d. Your letter dated September 16, 2016 set the audit to the information relating to T1135;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>e. Your letter dated September 16, 2016 stated that the CRA &ldquo;is in possession of information that has led us to determined that you have offshore holdings that you have failed to disclose as required by the Income Tax Act;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and,</P1>
<P1>f. The CRA letter, dated January 20, 2017, with respect to reasonable length of time to comply with the initial letter dated September 16, 2016 is onerous because information is located outside Canada.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>42. Further, the representative requests another six (6) month extension.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>43. In a letter dated April 5, 2017 the auditor stated in the first paragraph that &ldquo;as outlined previously, the Canada Revenue Agency is in possession of information that indicates that the taxpayers may have offshore interests that they failed to disclose as required by the Income Tax Act. Consequently, they have been selected for audit for the above noted period.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit I and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 15.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>44. The auditor made no reference to sections 231.2 and 231.6 of the Income Tax Act and the letter does not properly explain the consequences of non-compliance.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit I and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 15.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>45. In a letter dated May 4, 2017, <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;J&rdquo;</BOLD>, the representative for the respondent had concerns regarding the audit being improperly administered under the Income Tax Act of Canada including but not limited to (1) Overstated CRA authority; (2) Unclear audit Scope and Purpose; (3) Misapplication Under Section 231.7 of the Income Tax Act and in particular paragraph 231.7(1)(a); (4) section 152 of the Income Tax Act, which relates to the statute Barred years issue; (5) Other entities under audit as stated in the original letter dated September 16, 2016; and T1134 issue with respect to the 2015 taxation year.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit J and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 16.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>46. According to paragraph 17 of the auditor's affidavit, the auditor and the auditor's Team Leader had a telephone conversation with Mr. Hu to discuss the issues raised in his' letter May 4, 2017.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Douab Affidavit</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> note 2, at para 17.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>47. Further, the representative requested in person meeting with CRA with respect to audit, and during the meeting, the representative would provide answers to the questionnaire contained in the Demand Letter.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para 17.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>48. In a fax dated May 18 2017, the team leader thanked the representative of the respondent for confirmation the June 2, 2017 date for a meeting.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit K and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 18.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>49. Further, the team leader stated it would be beneficial if the taxpayers attended the meeting.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>50. In a letter dated May 19, 2017, the representative for the respondent confirmed the meeting but did not confirm the attendance of the respondent.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit L and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 19.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>51. Further, he advised the auditor that he will attend the meeting with the &ldquo;required questionnaire information and documents.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>52. The auditor stated that his team leader confirmed the June 2, 2017 meeting and expressed their intention to also meet with the respondent.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 20.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>53. Further, Canada Revenue Agency did not specifically require or demand that the respondent to attend the meeting, and the June 2, 2017 meeting is well beyond the 30 days provided for compliance in the auditor's April 5, 2017 letter.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>54. At the meeting, my authorized representative made oral and written submissions on my behalf with respect to my residency status for the purposes of taxation in Canada.</P>
<P>55. Mr. Hu provided a three page written submission &ldquo;Determination of Mr. Xue Lin's Residency for Tax Purpose&rdquo;.</P>
<P>56. At the June 2, 2017 meeting, the auditor provided the respondent with a letter dated June 2, 2017 and the letter was entitled. &ldquo;Re: Audit of your Income Tax Returns for the Period from January 1, 2006, to December 31, 2015&rdquo;.</P>
<P>57. Further, the letter stated that CRA had conducted a bank deposits and withdrawal analysis and thus requested further details with respect to some transactions that CRA were not able to reconcile.</P>
<P>58. Xue Lin was unable to attend the June 2, 2017 meeting because in China and was working.</P>
<P>59. Lin Lin did not attend the meeting because she was in China providing personal support care for my mother, due to her Alzheimer's condition, and as a result Lin Lin's authorized representative, Sean Hu, and Lin Lin's mother, Min Wang, provided documents from Lin Lin, a completed questionnaire and answered questions verbally on her behalf.</P>
<P>60. The &ldquo;respondent provided a partially answered version of the questionnaire that was attached to the Demand Letter.&rdquo;, and the auditor &ldquo;provided the [R]epresentative with a query and gave the [R]espondent 30 days to respond to it.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 21.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>61. There is no evidence that any CRA notes were prepared in regards to the June 2, 2017 meeting.</P>
<P>62. Further, CRA did not provide the respondent, nor the respondent's representative, with a receipt for documents that were provided to CRA.</P>
<P>63. In a letter dated May 4, 2017, the respondent requested another extension for two months because (1) the respondent will go back to China in order to prepare the documents and information; and (2) her dog is expected to give birth in a month or so.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit K and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 17.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>64. The June 20, 2017 letter from CRA provides another extension to August 18, 2016, and referred to &ldquo;requested&rdquo; information, and the letter does not discuss the consequence of non-compliance.</P>
<P>65. In a letter dated July 4, 2017 the representative of the respondent informed the auditor that the September 16, 2016 letter is not enforceable for the following reasons: (1) Unknown taxpayers selected for the audit and required to provide information; (2) Misapplication of the Income Tax Act&mdash;section 231.1; (3) Non-compliance with the Income Tax Act&mdash;section 233.4 of the Income Tax Act; (4) The statutorily barred years&mdash;section 152 of the Income Tax Act; (5) False Representation in the September 16, 2016 letter; and (6) Confusing correspondence from CRA.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit Q and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 25.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>66. In particular Sean Hu wanted a response to his written submissions to CRA because it was important to first determine if he is considered a resident of Canada for the purposes of taxation prior to ascertaining if he has any obligation to give any information to CRA pursuant to 231.1 of the ITA.</P>
<P>67. The auditor and the team leader contacted the representative of the respondent to &ldquo;get clarification on his July 4, 2017 letter&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Douab Affidavit</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> note 2 at para 25.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>68. The auditor did not attach his notes as an exhibit with respect to the above noted conversation with the respondent's representative.</P>
<P>69. In a letter dated August 4, 2017 the auditor provided a response to the respondent's representative's letter dated July 4, 2017.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit R and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 27.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>70. CRA's letter does not discuss the consequence of 231.7, except that it states it is a civil remedy.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>71. In a letter dated August 11, 2017, the representative for the respondent once again advised the auditor of the concerns he has with respect to this audit.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit S and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 28.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>72. Further, the representative for the respondent asked the auditor &ldquo;what are exactly the documents and information that remain outstanding from your initial letter dated September 16, 2017.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>73. The respondent's representative further stated the following: &ldquo;But what exactly are you demanding as far as your initial letter is concerned? You are talking as if the taxpayers had submitted nothing to you. Do you remember they submitted to you the information for the questionnaire and other documents such as bank statements during the meeting on June 2? They also answered your questions and you took notes.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>74. Further to the above, the representative for the respondent stated the following:
<QUOTE><P>it is understandable for your initial letter to outline your request in rather general terms before the audit started, but what we do not understand is that, two months after you received the information, you don't seem to have a better idea of what you want and to be able to let us know specifically what document or information is still outstanding based on the information already provided. We don't really see the reasons why you are still insisting on the whole package of your initial request.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>75. The auditor did not receive the &ldquo;information requested&rdquo; as per the Demand Letter.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 28.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>76. The auditor &ldquo;decided to initiate a request to the Department of Justice to pursue a compliance order pursuant to ss.231.7 of the <EM>ITA</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 29.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>77. The Director of the International and Ottawa Tax Service office sent a letter to the Department of Justice, Tax Law Services, requesting that a compliance order application be pursued in this matter.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 30.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>78. A letter dated December 1, 2017 from the Department of Justice, Canada referred to the Demand Letter of September 16, 2016 and stated that only four (4) questions from the questionnaire were still unanswered.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit T and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 32.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>79. Further, the letter from Department of Justice provided for a final extension to December 20, 2017, and the letter does not explain the consequences of non-compliance.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>80. In a letter dated December 20, 2017, Mr. Hu advised stated that the September 16, 2016 letter is unenforceable since it relates to years beyond the retention period.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit U and <EM>Douab Affidavit</EM> at para 33.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>81. Further, Mr. Hu states that (1) the available documents were provided at the June 2, 2017 meeting and (2) no receipt was provided for the documents provided.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>82. In particular, he asked the Department of Justice lawyer the same question that he asked the auditor, from the Offshore Compliance Division in the International and Ottawa Tax Services Office of the Canada Revenue agency for a response to his repeated request for the determination of Mr. Xue Lin's residency status in Canada for the purpose of section 231.1.</P>
<P>83. The auditor stated that to date, he had still not received all of the books, records, or information as set out in the Demand Letter sent pursuant to ss. 231.1(1) of the <EM>Act</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>84. Throughout the entirety of correspondence between the auditor and the respondent, &ldquo;books and records&rdquo; were never requested or demanded.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III"><UNDER>PART II&mdash;ISSUES</UNDER></TI>
<P>85. The Court must use statutory interpretation in order to ascertain if the Minister has the authority to request information pursuant to subsection 231.1 of the ITA.</P>
<P>86. The Court must additionally look at the specific facts of this case in order to determine where the issuance of the letter and questionnaire are within the parameters of subsection 231.1(1) of the ITA.</P>
<P>87. Whether CRA can use their audit powers under 231.1 of the ITA prior to the determination of Mr. Xue Lin's tax status in Canada in this case.</P>
<P>88. The respondent has raised the issue whether the Minister is entitled under s.231.7 of the ITA to compel the respondent to provide responses to the September 16, 2016 letter and the questionnaire.</P>
<P>89. The respondent has raised the issue whether the conditions for the issuance of a compliance order under ss. 231.7 of ITA are met in the present case.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI>Minister's power to inspect, audit and examine books, records and property</TI>
<P>90. The Minister of National Revenue must be given broad powers in the supervising this regulatory scheme to audit taxpayers' returns and inspect all records that may relevant to the preparation of those returns.</P>
<P>91. The Minister's argument that &ldquo;inspect, audit and examine&rdquo; in subsection 231.1 includes the authority to request information.</P>
<P>92. Statutory interpretation precludes the Minister from requesting information pursuant to subsection 231.1 because that would ignore the mid-amble of the section that expressly restricts assistance for the purposes of allowing the Minister to &ldquo;inspect, audit or examine&rdquo; the books, records and property of the respondent.</P>
<P>93. Section 231.1(2) of the ITA deals with requirement for information relating to &ldquo;unnamed persons&rdquo;.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>PART III&mdash;SUBMISSIONS</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>How these principles apply to the facts of this instance</TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER>Temporal Scope of the Compliance Audit</UNDER></TI>
<P>94. With respect to paragraph 4 of the auditor's affidavit, on September 2, 2016, the auditor stated that he was assigned a compliance audit for the years 2006 to 2015. This is unlikely, depending on the initial assessment dates for each of the years. Most of those years were likely statute barred. According to subsection 152(4), CRA can only assess or reassess a return prior to the statute barred date if the CRA had, at the very least, evidence of misrepresentation attributable to negligence, carelessness, or willful default. It is inconsistent for CRA to start an audit of years as far back as above-noted taxation years unless they were confident that they could reassess. This would suggest that they had evidence of neglect, carelessness, or willful default, which generally amounts to a violation of the Income Tax Act before the audit started.</P>
<P>95. With respect to paragraph 5 of the auditor's affidavit, the auditor stated that in order to conduct the audit, he needs to review various books, records and documents. However, none of the documents attached as Exhibits indicate that he ever asked for &ldquo;books and records&rdquo;. The auditor asked for information in the form of the answering of questions that were supplied, and indirectly for documents to support the answers, however there was no mention of the books and records.</P>
<P>96. With respect to paragraph 5 of the auditor's affidavit, the respondent was not was not informed as to what led to the request for information other than &ldquo;Canada Revenue Agency is in possession of information that has led us to determine that you might have offshore holdings that you have failed to disclose as required by the Income Tax Act.&rdquo;</P>
<P>97. With respect to paragraph 5 of the auditor's affidavit, the auditor does not does not use clear language to justify requesting to obtain information from the respondent. The auditor could have simply stated that we are aware that you have foreign bank accounts (please see June 2, 2017 letter from the Minister) and thus we want to &ldquo;inspect, audit or examine&rdquo; your books, records and property pursuant to subsection 231.1 of the ITA.</P>
<P>98. With respect to paragraph 5 of the auditor's affidavit, the respondent was not aware if the auditor met with or talked to an investigator in the investigations division.</P>
<P>99. With respect to paragraph 5 of the auditor's affidavit, the respondent was not informed as to what the Minister was trying to determine with respect to their correct tax liability under the Act for 2006 to 2015 tax returns.</P>
<P>100. With respect to paragraph 5 of the auditor's affidavit, the Applicant cannot demonstrate that the Requirement for Information was made as a part of an audit of Respondent's 2006 to 2015 taxation years and that the information and documents being sought therein are &ldquo;necessary to confirm the respondent's compliance with the ITA&rdquo;.</P>
<P>101. With respect to paragraph 5 of the auditor's affidavit, the respondent submits that the purpose of the letter and questionnaire was to allow the Minister to engage on a fishing expedition in an attempt to obtain information and thus did not afford the respondent an opportunity to seek legal advice with respect self-incrimination, for example.</P>
<P>102. With respect to paragraph 5 of the auditor's affidavit, the Requirement for Information that was requested was for another purpose other than a tax audit conducted in good faith.</P>
<P>103. With respect to paragraph 6 of the auditor's affidavit, the auditor states that on September 16, 2016 he sent a registered letter to the taxpayer advising Lin Lin of the compliance audit and that the letter included a questionnaire. Section 244(5) states that the affidavit is to include documentary proof of the registration and there is no proof of service for the above-noted registered mail.</P>
<P>104. With respect to paragraph 6 of the auditor's affidavit, the auditor states that on September 16, 2016 he sent a registered letter to the taxpayer advising Lin Lin of the compliance audit and that the letter included a questionnaire. Section 244(5) states that the affidavit is include to documentary proof of the registration and there is no proof of service for the above-noted registered mail.</P>
<P>105. With regard to the first condition, in the case at bar, it is unclear whether 231.1 or 231.2 requirement was addressed to the respondent or any other related or associated entities.</P>
<P>106. The request for information was addressed to Lin Lin in her personal capacity.</P>
<P>107. The fact that the salutation of the request for information was &ldquo;Dear Lin Lin&rdquo; supports the view that the address was to Lin Lin and not any other related or associated entities.</P>
<P>108. It is not clear whether the request, nor requirement, was directed to the respondent personally or any other related or associated entities from which the Minister also seeks information</P>
<P>109. In addition, the threatened penal sanction in the request for information reinforces the position that the request pertained to Ms. Lin in her personal capacity, and not any other related or associated entities, since a corporation cannot be imprisoned.</P>
<P>110. In light of the uncertainty as to whether the request was addressed to Lin Lin or any other related or associated entities, the first condition cannot be said to be satisfied.</P>
<P>111. Section 231.2 of the ITA deals with requests for information relating to &ldquo;unnamed persons&rdquo;, not subsection 231.1 of the ITA.</P>
<P>112. The authority to request information is given in subsection 231.2 (1) of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, as long as it relates to named persons. In this case, other than the taxpayer, the other persons (entities) are not named, although CRA's letter suggests that they had such information. If CRA wants information on unnamed persons, they need judicial authorization and the reason is to avoid a &ldquo;fishing expedition&rdquo;.</P>
<P>113. Further, it is recognized that the new section (now section 231.2(3)), dealing with requests for information relating to &ldquo;unnamed persons&rdquo;, required a strict interpretation because of its intrusive nature into the right to the protection of private information.</P>
<P>114. Pursuant to subsection 231.2 of the ITA, &ldquo;Any other related or associated entities&rdquo; is not a group that is ascertainable, nor is the information sought in order to make it possible to verify compliance with the Act.</P>
<P>115. With respect to paragraph 6 of the auditor's affidavit, the request, and not the requirement, for information is broader than a straightforward list because of the words &ldquo;whether or not registered in your name is included in the questionnaire&rdquo;. This choice of language raises a question of whether the respondent is being asked to list his personal assets or to include documentation about corporate assets that he would only have access to in his capacity as a director or officer of a corporation.</P>
<P>116. With respect to paragraph 6 of the auditor's affidavit, the auditor refers to September 16, 2016 registered letter as the &ldquo;Demand Letter&rdquo; and states that it is issued pursuant to subsection 231.1 of the ITA. The 16 September letter is not a &ldquo;Demand Letter&rdquo; because the letter only asks for information and makes no statement that a response is &ldquo;required&rdquo;.</P>
<P>117. With respect to paragraph 6 of the auditor's affidavit, 16 September did not set out the consequences for non-compliance. The letter sent makes no reference to consequences and therefore is only an initial request and not a Demand nor a Requirement.</P>
<P>118. Subsection 231.1 of the ITA states that the auditor is authorized to review certain things, and as noted in this section of the Income Tax Act, relates to books, records, of a business or property of a business, not obtaining information. This is summarized by the subheading <BOLD>&ldquo;Inspections&rdquo;</BOLD> at the beginning of the section. The reference to answering &ldquo;all proper questions&rdquo; relates to asking the owner or manager of the property that has been entered into. In addition, auditors are entitled to be provided with &ldquo;all reasonable assistance&rdquo; in performing their audits (paragraph 231.1(1)(d) of the Act). In this case, no books and records were requested for inspection and thus subsection 231.1(1) does not apply.</P>
<P>119. The procedure used to be first of all, a &ldquo;request&rdquo; would be served on the taxpayer, providing a deadline for the provision of the books and records (ss.231.1) or information or documents (ss.231.2). If the taxpayer did not comply, a &ldquo;demand&rdquo; or &ldquo;requirement&rdquo; letter would be issued with evidence of personal service. This would provide another deadline but would spell out the consequences for non-compliance. If the taxpayer still did not comply, then a recommendation would be made for a charge under section 238 of the ITA.</P>
<P>120. Subsection 238(1) of the Act provides the following:
<P1>a.
<QUOTE><SEC><N>238.</N><SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>Every one who had failed to file or make a return as and when required by or under this Act or a regulation or who has failed to comply with subsection 116(3), 127(3.1) or 127(3.2), 147(7) or 153(1), any of sections 230 to 232 or a regulation made under subsection 147.1 (18) or with an order under subsection 238(2) is guilty of an offence and, in addition to any penalty otherwise provided, is liable on summary conviction to
<PARA><N>i.</N><PARAP>a fine of not less than $1,000 and not more than $25,000.00; or</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>ii.</N><PARAP>both the fine described in paragraph 238(1) (a) and imprisonment for a term not exceeding 12 months.</PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE></P1></P>
<P>121. With respect to paragraph 6 of the auditor's affidavit, there can be no formal extensions given in regard to a &ldquo;Demand Letter&rdquo;. If a formal extension is given, there needs to be a new &ldquo;Demand Letter&rdquo;. The fact that numerous extensions were given, supports the fact that at least the original letter was not a &ldquo;Demand Letter&rdquo;.</P>
<P>122. With respect to paragraph 6 of the auditor's affidavit, if it is meant to be a &ldquo;Demand Letter&rdquo;, it is inconsistent to not use the word &ldquo;require&rdquo; instead of &ldquo;request&rdquo;.</P>
<P>123. With respect to paragraph 9 of the auditor's affidavit, the auditor states that in his correspondence to the taxpayer's representative dated November 7, 2016, that he &ldquo;reiterated the demand for the respondent to provide information requested in Demand Letter&rdquo;. Note that he acknowledges that he was asking for &ldquo;information&rdquo; and not &ldquo;books and records&rdquo;.</P>
<P>124. With respect to paragraph 9 of the auditor's affidavit, the letter dated November 7, 2016 states &ldquo;We ask that you please provide information requested as outlined in our initial letter dated September 16, 2016 within 10 days of this letter.&rdquo; Again, no &ldquo;Demand&rdquo;, but a request and no consequence presented if there is non-compliance.</P>
<P>125. With respect to paragraph 11 of the auditor's affidavit, the auditor does not call it a &ldquo;Demand&rdquo; in this paragraph. He refers to &ldquo;the requested information and documents&rdquo;, and provides a formal extension. The reply letter from the auditor again refers to &ldquo;the information requested&rdquo;, not demanded or required. The auditor then said that if the information is not received they will pursue issuing a Compliance Order under ss. 231.7(1), which requires judicial approval. This could be seen to escalate the matter from a Request to an Order, while skipping any actual Demand. In order to take this step, the judge would have to be satisfied that the person was properly <BOLD><UNDER>required</UNDER></BOLD> or <BOLD><UNDER>demanded</UNDER></BOLD>, under section 231.1 or 231.2 to provide the access, assistance, information or document (as applicable) and did not do so.</P>
<P>126. With respect to paragraph 12 of the auditor's affidavit, again the auditor refers to the original letter as a Demand Letter. The questions raised by Mr. Hu dealt with procedural issues concerning the answering of the questions. Mr. Hu also raised the issue of a &ldquo;reasonable time&rdquo; if the request is made under 231.6, which allows for a minimum of 90 days to respond. This seems valid, although the auditor had not actually made the request under that Section. There were also issues about travel to meet with the auditor and a request was made to move the audit to Toronto.</P>
<P>127. With respect to paragraph 13 of the auditor's affidavit, it took the auditor about 4 weeks to reply to the representative. In that reply, the deadline was extended once again, this time to January 20, 2017. On the cover page, the auditor said that this was allowing the taxpayer more than 90 days. He also called the information &ldquo;requested information&rdquo; and the original letter a &ldquo;request letter&rdquo;. He also references the original letter was being dated September 22, 2016, which is not attached as an Exhibit. The response references September 22, 2016 as being the original letter. There is also a reference to an &ldquo;initial letter dated September 16, 2016&rdquo;. The reference is made that the auditor will be pursuing a Compliance Order, although the cover of the fax gives them until January 20<SUP>th</SUP>.</P>
<P>128. With respect to paragraph 14 of the auditor's affidavit, the representative asks further questions and requests a 6-month extension. He raises some valid points and provides reasons for the extension request. The questions again deal with procedural issues surrounding the questionnaire.</P>
<P>129. With respect to paragraph 15 of the auditor's affidavit, it is apparent that some portion of the extension requested was granted since the next letter the auditor refers to is dated April 5, 2017. The auditor makes no reference to a request under subsection 231.2 or 231.6, only 231.1.</P>
<P>130. With respect to paragraph 16 of the auditor's affidavit, the May 4, 2017 letter from the representative raises the issue as to whether the September 16, 2016 letter was addressed to the respondent in his personal capacity, or addressed to a corporation. Because of the uncertainty as to who the letter was addressed to, the criteria in section 231.1 or 231.2 has not been satisfied and in particular raised concerns that the audit was not being properly administered under the Act. As a result, paragraph 231.7(1)(a) has not been satisfied because the entity is not identified. The representative also referred to Section 152 relating to statute barred years and that the taxpayer has no obligation to provide evidence to CRA to satisfy Section 152. At the bottom of the third page, Mr. Hu acknowledges the &ldquo;Demand&rdquo; but questions the authority.</P>
<P>131. With respect to paragraph 17 of the auditor's affidavit, it is noted that both the auditor and his team leader had a telephone conversation with Mr. Hu on May 17, 2017; however, there is no reference to any notes prepared in relation to these conversations and they are not attached as Exhibits.</P>
<P>132. With respect to paragraph 19 of the auditor's affidavit, Exhibit L from Mr. Hu confirms the meeting for June 2, 2017, however, it does not confirm that his clients would be there.</P>
<P>133. With respect to paragraph 20 of the auditor's affidavit, <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;M&rdquo;</BOLD> from the team leader confirms the meeting on June 2, 2017 and voices their intention to also meet with the clients. CRA did not require or demand that the clients be at the meeting. This meeting is well beyond the 30 days provided for compliance in the auditor's April 5, 2017 letter. This nullifies any Demand implied by that letter.</P>
<P>134. With respect to paragraph 21 of the auditor's affidavit, a meeting took place on June 2, 2017 with the auditor, his team leader, and the authorized representative, Sean Hu. There is no evidence that any notes were prepared in regard to their meeting, since they are not referenced nor attached as Exhibits. Therefore, there is nothing to support the apparent further extension to July 4, 2017, other than a reference in the affidavit of an additional 30 days. Once again, this nullifies any prior Demand. There is no record or reference made to what was discussed.</P>
<P>135. The respondent provided responses to the queries on June 2, 2017.</P>
<P>136. At the June 2, 2017 meeting there was no suggestion that CRA found the respondent hesitant and reluctant at times when answering questions and not personally knowledgeable with respect to the questionnaire.</P>
<P>137. The respondent says that he has made significant effort and complied with all requests for the information that is the subject of this application.</P>
<P>138. With respect to paragraph 23 of the auditor's affidavit, the June 20, 2017 letter from CRA refers to &ldquo;requested&rdquo; information, not required information or demanded information. This is another extension, which nullifies the prior requests.</P>
<P>139. With respect to paragraph 24 of the auditor's affidavit, <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;Q&rdquo;</BOLD> refers to a July 4, 2017 letter from the respondent's representative in which Sean Hu raised the issue of enforceability of subsection 231.1(1). It cannot be ascertained whether the September 16, 2016 letter was addressed to the respondent in her personal capacity or to unnamed entities. As a result, we cannot ascertain who is the person being referred to in paragraph (a) of section 231.7(1)(a) and addressing that Xue Lin is considered a non-resident for the purposes of taxation.</P>
<P>140. With respect to paragraph 25 of the auditor's affidavit, there should be notes referenced and attached in regard to the conversation on July 7, 2017.</P>
<P>141. With respect to paragraph 26 of the auditor's affidavit, the referenced letter dated August 4, 2017 ignores Mr. Hu's concerns about the non-use of s. 231.2. Note the use of the word &ldquo;request&rdquo; by the auditor, and that in this case no extension was agreed to.</P>
<P>142. With respect to paragraph 27 of the auditor's affidavit, <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;S&rdquo;,</BOLD> the auditor received a letter from Sean Hu in which he requested another face to face meeting in order to clarify the issues as presented in the August 4, 2017 letter. Among many other issues, in the August 11, 2017 letter, Mr. Hu addressed the subject of section 231.1 with regard to the enforceability of the September 16, 2016 letter, the non-residency of Xue Lin, and the confusion surrounding what CRA is requesting of the respondent.</P>
<P>143. With respect to paragraph 31 of the auditor's affidavit, the letter from the Justice Department provided a final extension to December 20, 2017. Reference is made to the &ldquo;Demand Letter&rdquo; of September 16, 2016.</P>
<P>144. With respect to paragraph 32 of the auditor's affidavit, <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;U&rdquo;</BOLD> is a letter from Mr. Hu to the Department of Justice. Mr. Hu states that the available documents were provided at the June 2, 2017 meeting. He also states that no receipt was provided for the documents produced.</P>
<P>145. With respect to paragraph 33 of the auditor's affidavit, books and records were never requested or demanded.</P>
<P>146. With respect to paragraph 34 of the auditor's affidavit, it would be correct that the auditor only does audits and not investigations, however, that does not mean that he was working with an investigator, or in conjunctions with the Investigation Division.</P>
<P>147. It should be kept in mind that the auditor would have had the option of obtaining production orders for any banks that he was aware of through the client's tax returns or third-party information. The auditor could then have proposed to reassess the client on any unexplained amounts deposited into the bank accounts.</P>
<P>148. A letter dated December 1, 2017 indicated that several queries remain outstanding as of December 1, 2017 and continue to be pursued in this application.</P>
<P>149. As of the date of this application, the respondent has provided a satisfactory response to 4 of the queries (2.1, 2.2, 2.3, and 2.4) of the questionnaire.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER>Conclusion</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK5><TI><UNDER>Statutory Interpretation and Subsection 231.1 of the ITA</UNDER></TI>
<P>150. Discrete sections of the ITA must be viewed in light of the other provisions of the Act and the purpose of the legislation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Ruth Sullivan, <EM>Construction of Statutes</EM>, (Canada: LexisNexis, 2014) at 635.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The court must &ldquo;analyze a given transaction in the context of economic and commercial realty, but these techniques cannot alter the result where the words of the statute are plain and where the legal and practical effect of the transaction is undisputed.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at 635.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> It is a well-established basic concept in tax law that &ldquo;where the taxing statute is not explicit, reasonable uncertainty or factual ambiguity resulting from lack of explicitness in the statute should be resolved in favour of the taxpayer.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at 639.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> If the ordinary principles of interpretation do not firmly resolve the issue, &ldquo;any doubt about the meaning of a taxation statute must be reasonable.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at 640.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This is considered a &ldquo;residual presumption of last resort&rdquo; and &ldquo;only a reasonable doubt, not resolved by ordinary rules of interpretation, will be settled by recourse to the residual presumption in favour of the taxpayer.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at 639-40.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>151. Subsection 231.1 of the ITA authorizes an auditor to inspect a taxpayer's books, records as they pertain to the business or property of the business. As a result, a taxpayer is obligated to answer all proper questions that relate to the taxpayer's books and records. In addition, auditors are entitled to be provided with &ldquo;all reasonable assistance&rdquo; in performing their audits (paragraph 231. 1(1)(d) of the Act). In this case, no books, records were required for inspection and thus subsection 231.1(1) does not apply.</P>
<P>152. Subsection 231.1 of the ITA states that the auditor is authorized to do certain things and these certain things noted in this section of the Income Tax Act relates to books, records, of a business or property of a business, not obtaining information. This is summarized by the subheading &ldquo;<BOLD>Inspections</BOLD>&rdquo; at the beginning of the section. The reference to answering &ldquo;all proper questions&rdquo; relates to asking the owner or manager of the property that has been entered into. In addition, auditors are entitled to be provided with &ldquo;all reasonable assistance&rdquo; in performing their audits (paragraph 231.1(1)(d) of the Act). In this case, no books and/or records were requested for inspection and thus subsection 231.1(1) does not apply.</P>
<P>153. Statutory interpretation of subsection of 231.1 of the ITA in this specific instance precludes the Minister from requesting information pursuant to subsection 231.1 of the ITA.</P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER>Tax Residency</UNDER></TI>
<P>154. Mr. Xue Lin is a resident of China for tax purposes because his &ldquo;central vital interests&rdquo; lie in China or he is deemed to be a resident of the Contracting State of which he is a national of, China.</P>
<P>155. For the abovementioned reason, he is not considered a person &ldquo;required under subsection 231.1 or 231.2 to provide the access, assistance, information or document and did not do so&rdquo; pursuant to paragraph 231.7(a) of the ITA.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER>The Test of subsection 231.7 of the ITA</UNDER></TI>
<P>156. As set out at paragraph of 231.7 (a) of the ITA, one must ascertain if the respondent is considered a person &ldquo;required under subsection of 231.1&rdquo; of the ITA &ldquo;to provide the access, assistance, information or document&rdquo;.</P>
<P>157. The respondent is not necessarily a person that is required to provide access, assistance, information or documents because the September 16, 2016 letter is not clear whether the request for information was directed to the respondent personally or to various other associations and thus the Court should not exercise it discretion to issue the requested compliance order.</P>
<P>158. Next, as the test is set out at paragraph 231.7(b) of the ITA, one must ascertain if the respondent is &ldquo;required&rdquo; to comply with the Minister's request for information.</P>
<P>159. If the Court determines that the Minister has the authority to request information pursuant to subsection 231.1 of the ITA in this case, the respondent submits that the Applicant has not met its burden to prove that the respondent has not already provided the requested information.</P>
<P>160. In the alternative, if the Court determines that the Minister has the authority to request information pursuant to subsection 231.1 of the ITA and the respondent has not provided satisfactory response to four (4) of the queries (2.1, 2.2, 2.3, and 2.4) of the questionnaire, the respondent will provide information if the CRA make it clear what specific documents are outstanding.</P>
<P>161. The respondent argues that it is not reasonable for the Applicant to seek a compliance order against the respondent when none of the CRA representatives provided the respondent with the necessary information that the CRA representatives had as to what was required in order for the respondent to comply with the queries.</P>
<P>162. The test set out at paragraph 231.7(1)(a) of the ITA is relevant because if the respondent &ldquo;was required under section 231.1 or 231.2 to provide the access, assistance, information or document...&rdquo; but the respondent and the respondent's authorized representative clearly indicated numerous times a lack of understanding as to what remaining outstanding information is required, the respondent would logically be unable to provide it.</P>
<P>163. Thus, the test, which the jurisprudence indicates must be &ldquo;clearly met,&rdquo; has not been fulfilled for the issuance of an order under s.271.1</P>
<P>164. The respondent argues that the Minister had failed to &ldquo;clearly meet&rdquo; her burden to show that the respondent had not already provided the documents or, in the alternative, that the documents will be provided if CRA provides clarification what was specifically outstanding.</P>
<P>165. If CRA requires clarification with respect to four queries, it may make further inquiries, but argues that no basis exists for this Court to make as 231.7 order requiring the production of further information.</P>
<P>166. In the event that the Court is satisfied that the Applicant has &ldquo;clearly met&rdquo; the burden to prove that the respondent was required under 231.1 to provide the information sought by the Applicant, then the respondent submits that the Court ought to exercise its discretion not to issue the order.</P>
<P>167. The test set out at paragraph 231.7(c) of the ITA the information and documents are protected by solicitor-client privilege and the aforementioned paragraph does not apply to the case at bar.</P>
<BLOCK5><TI><UNDER>Potentially Serious Consequences</UNDER></TI>
<P>168. In addition, there are potentially serious consequences that can flow from the failure to obey a compliance order, including fines and/or imprisonment. In light of this, the Court indicated in <CASEREF><SOC>Minister of National Revenue v SML Operations (Canada LTD)</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><CITE>2003 FC 868</CITE></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> that it would not exercise its discretion to order the production of the documents sought by the Minister unless it was satisfied that the statutory conditions of section 231.7 of the <EM>ITA</EM> had been &ldquo;clearly met&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM> at para 15.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV"><UNDER>PART IV&mdash;ORDER SOUGHT</UNDER></TI>
<P>169.The Respondent requests that the Applicant be dismissed with costs.</P>
